  "prompt": "What does job screening mean?",
  "response": "Job screening is the process employers use to evaluate and assess candidates during the hiring process to determine their suitability for a specific role. It involves reviewing and filtering applications, resumes, and other relevant information to identify the most qualified individuals who match the job requirements. Key steps in job screening typically include:\n\n1. **Resume/CV Review**  \n   Employers scan resumes for qualifications, skills, experience, and education that align with the job description.\n\n2. **Application Review**  \n   Candidates may fill out job applications that provide additional details, such as work history, certifications, or references.\n\n3. **Pre-Screening Questions**  \n   Some employers include specific questions in the application to assess a candidate's fit for the role or company culture.\n\n4. **Phone/Video Screening**  \n   A preliminary interview (often short) to gauge interest, availability, and basic qualifications.\n\n5. **Background Checks**  \n   Verification of a candidate\u2019s employment history, education, criminal record, or other relevant details.\n\n6. **Skills Assessments**  \n   Tests or exercises to evaluate a candidate\u2019s technical skills, problem-solving abilities, or job-specific competencies.\n\n7. **Reference Checks**  \n   Contacting previous employers or professional references to learn more about the candidate\u2019s performance and work ethic.\n\nJob screening helps employers reduce the pool of applicants to those who best meet the job criteria, saving time and resources in the hiring process.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
